cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 115 mi ESE of Marathon, Florida
cyclone.trajectory: moving north-northwest through the Florida Straits tonight, then turning west into the southeastern Gulf of Mexico Monday-Tuesday, eventually curving north toward the eastern Gulf coast later in the week
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: Florida Keys (near or over the Keys)

weather_observation.watch_coast: Florida coast from north of Englewood to Anna Maria Island (tropical-storm watch area)
weather_observation.warning_coast: Florida coast from Brevard/Volusia County line southward around the Keys to Englewood (tropical-storm warning area)
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Entire south and central Florida peninsula, Keys, and adjacent Atlantic and Gulf coasts
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force winds (39-55 mph with higher gusts) possible Monday as Eta passes south and then west of the port.
weather_observation.storm_surge: 1–2 ft of surge/inundation possible along the central Florida Atlantic coast, including Port Canaveral, especially at high tide.
weather_observation.rainfall: 6–12 inches of rainfall possible across central Florida with locally higher amounts, producing urban and localized flash flooding.
weather_observation.other_hazards: Dangerous rip currents; isolated tornadoes cannot be ruled out in outer rainbands.
